              Euler, Thomas and Roman-Roson, Miroslav and Theis, Lucas and
              Tolias, Andreas S and Bethge, Matthias",
  abstract = "In recent years, two-photon calcium imaging has become a standard
              tool to probe the function of neural circuits and to study
              computations in neuronal populations. However, the acquired
              signal is only an indirect measurement of neural activity due to
              the comparatively slow dynamics of fluorescent calcium
              indicators. Different algorithms for estimating spike trains from
              noisy calcium measurements have been proposed in the past, but it
              is an open question how far performance can be improved. Here, we
              report the results of the spikefinder challenge, launched to
