               Denk, Winfried and Korogod, Natalya and Knott, Graham and
               Koethe, Ullrich and Hamprecht, Fred A",
  abstract  = "We address the problem of partitioning a volume image into a
               previously unknown number of segments, based on a likelihood of
               merging adjacent supervoxels. Towards this goal, we adapt a
               higher-order probabilistic graphical model that makes the
               duality between supervoxels and their joint faces explicit and
               ensures that merging decisions are consistent and surfaces of
               final segments are closed. First, we propose a practical
               cutting-plane approach to solve the MAP inference problem to
