  abstract      = "Feed-forward convolutional neural networks (CNNs) are
                   currently state-of-the-art for object classification tasks
                   such as ImageNet. Further, they are quantitatively accurate
                   models of temporally-averaged responses of neurons in the
                   primate brain's visual system. However, biological visual
                   systems have two ubiquitous architectural features not
                   shared with typical CNNs: local recurrence within cortical
                   areas, and long-range feedback from downstream areas to
                   upstream areas. Here we explored the role of recurrence in
                   improving classification performance. We found that standard
                   forms of recurrence (vanilla RNNs and LSTMs) do not perform
