              tasks. This phenomenon is the result of ``catastrophic
              forgetting,'' in which training an ANN disrupts connection
              weights that were important for solving previous tasks, degrading
              task performance. Several recent studies have proposed methods to
              stabilize connection weights of ANNs that are deemed most
              important for solving a task, which helps alleviate catastrophic
              forgetting. Here, drawing inspiration from algorithms that are
              believed to be implemented in vivo, we propose a complementary
              method: adding a context-dependent gating signal, such that only
              sparse, mostly nonoverlapping patterns of units are active for
