                   accuracy is particularly pressing if two systems are near
                   ceiling performance, like Convolutional Neural Networks
                   (CNNs) and humans on visual object recognition. Here we
                   introduce trial-by-trial error consistency, a quantitative
                   analysis for measuring whether two decision making systems
                   systematically make errors on the same inputs. Making
                   consistent errors on a trial-by-trial basis is a necessary
                   condition for similar processing strategies between decision
                   makers. Our analysis is applicable to compare algorithms
                   with algorithms, humans with humans, and algorithms with
                   humans. When applying error consistency to object
                   recognition we obtain three main findings: (1.) Irrespective
                   of architecture, CNNs are remarkably consistent with one
                   another. (2.) The consistency between CNNs and human
                   observers, however, is little above what can be expected by
