  abstract      = "The visual system is hierarchically organized to process
                   visual information in successive stages. Neural
                   representations vary drastically across the first stages of
                   visual processing: at the output of the retina, ganglion
                   cell receptive fields (RFs) exhibit a clear antagonistic
                   center-surround structure, whereas in the primary visual
                   cortex, typical RFs are sharply tuned to a precise
                   orientation. There is currently no unified theory explaining
                   these differences in representations across layers. Here,
